{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492532"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:34:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:34:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1092"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1092"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.67,0.16,0.09,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1092"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33951"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1092"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1092"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19212"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"448"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6467"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6468"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8330"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8564"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/33951"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents with a four day history of crampy abdominal pain and distension, associated with absolute constipation. He suffers with chronic constipation and this was made worse after a recent hospitalisation for an episode of acute pancreatitis. He takes coloxyl regularly. On examination his abdomen is distended with generalised abdominal tenderness. He has normal bowel sounds. An abdominal X-ray is taken (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Simple constipation","Sigmoid volvulus","Pseudo-obstruction","Paralytic ileus","Carcinoma of the descending colon"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray shows a large, gas-filled loop of colon arising out of the pelvis. The shape of this loop is said to resemble a coffee bean and the shape, position and degree of distension are all characteristic and essentially pathognomonic of a \u003Cstrong\u003Esigmoid volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E. A volvulus is the twisting of the colon and its mesentery around on itself. This leads to a bowel obstruction due to the inability of stool to pass through the lumen of the colon at the point of the obstruction. Furthermore, a persistent volvulus can lead to pinching and obstruction of the colonic vessels present in the mesentery, resulting in ischaemic bowel. This could be followed by perforation. This patient already has abdominal tenderness, suggesting that some degree of vascular compromise has already occurred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor most cases of non-ischaemic sigmoid volvulus, decompression with by sigmoidoscopy (rigid or flexible) is the preferred treatment option and will provide rapid decompression and resolution of the problem. With a more complicated volvulus (ischaemic bowel or perforation), resection can be necessary. A typical patient with a sigmoid volvulus is one over the age of 70, with chronic constipation and living in residential care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple constipation\u003C/strong\u003E would not lead to such significant bowel dilation as seen on this X-ray and no faecal loading is seen. Moreover, it is unlikely to present with no flatulence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst a \u003Cstrong\u003Epseudo-obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered as a diagnosis, most of the large bowel is usually distended - and that is not the case here, where normal loops of ascending and transverse colon can be seen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParalytic ileus\u003C/strong\u003E is the reduction in normal bowel function most commonly occuring after abdominal intervention. Reasons include handling of the bowel, inflammation and medications (e.g. opiods). It shares many clinical features of this presentation, however X-ray features usually show no clear transition point and generalised uniform involvement of large and small bowel - features not seen on this X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarcinoma of the descending colon \u003C/strong\u003Emay lead to a large bowel obstruction, it usually has a chronic, insidious onset rather than the acute presentation seen here. In addition, the obstruction caused by such a tumour would lead to dilatation of most of the large bowel proximal to the tumour.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A plain abdominal X-ray is usually sufficient to identify and diagnose a bowel obstruction"],"references":["Jones J, Iqbal S, Molinari A, et al. Sigmoid volvulus. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org (Accessed on 22 Feb 2023) https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-6398","Radswiki T, Chieng R, Iqbal S, et al. Adynamic ileus. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org (Accessed on 22 Feb 2023) https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-12204"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19212"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1092"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19601"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19601"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7c113ab2-edc9-4210-8f5c-bcb530281742.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7c113ab2-edc9-4210-8f5c-bcb530281742.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":467,"height":600}},{"